  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically covered under criminal legislation. Specific laws and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but money laundering generally involves:\n\n1. Concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n2. Making illegally-obtained funds appear legal\n3. Transforming \"dirty\" money into \"clean\" money\n\nIn many countries, money laundering is prosecuted under:\n- Criminal codes\n- Anti-money laundering (AML) statutes\n- Financial crime regulations\n\nPenalties can include:\n- Substantial fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Professional sanctions\n\nMost developed nations have robust legal frameworks to combat money laundering, often requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and comply with strict reporting requirements.",
